INSERT DELAYED IGNORE INTO `posts` (`id`, `title`, `author_id`, `is_active`, `image`, `type_id`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1, 'Smartest Applications for Business', 1, 1, '/files/posts/jdV9e37cDpNPTNdOspX3QxbH6YEjd3gzphK1FYbu.jpg', 2, '<p>The most well-known dummy text is the \'Lorem Ipsum\', which is said to have originated in the 16th century. Lorem Ipsum is composed in a pseudo-Latin language which more or less corresponds to \'proper\' Latin. It contains a series of real Latin words. This ancient dummy text is also incomprehensible, but it imitates the rhythm of most European languages in Latin script.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>\" There are many variations of passages of Lorem Ipsum available, but the majority have suffered alteration in some form, by injected humour, or randomised words which don\'t look even slightly believable. \"</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The advantage of its Latin origin and the relative meaninglessness of Lorum Ipsum is that the text does not attract attention to itself or distract the viewer\'s attention from the layout.</p>', '2022-09-20 10:05:08', '2022-09-20 11:10:26'),
(4, 'Apple Event Unlikely This October Despite Many New Devices Expected', 1, 1, '/files/posts/hfvN4aLFQcDhp7aNruEGRjepw2cp0rJ9pLJ1e6i0.jpg', 2, '<p>This week also saw the launch of the iPhone 14 Plus, the last member of the iPhone 14 lineup to become available following last month\'s introduction. We\'re also looking forward to operating system updates coming soon, with a bug fix iOS update likely imminent and a more substantial iOS 16.1 one coming alongside iPadOS 16 and macOS Ventura, so read on for details on these stories and more!<br>While <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/05/apple-products-to-avoid-buying-right-now/\">new iPad and Mac models</a> are expected to be announced this month, <i>Bloomberg</i>\'s Mark Gurman believes that Apple is <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/02/gurman-doubles-down-on-no-october-event/\">unlikely to hold a media event in October this year</a>.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/anPClZKcM-Jo8GFujWtF9kB1RM8=/400x0/article-new/2021/05/ipad-pro-m1-feature.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"ipad pro m1 feature\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/anPClZKcM-Jo8GFujWtF9kB1RM8=/400x0/article-new/2021/05/ipad-pro-m1-feature.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/3FU9Ace-iiWg2HxGyzDgbTuOI6c=/800x0/article-new/2021/05/ipad-pro-m1-feature.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/7hZCaaMo4T4JV6eLoJX2ou4lyqI=/1600x0/article-new/2021/05/ipad-pro-m1-feature.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/ogVR6esOJBe2VoknZXOBTDaFsxA=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2021/05/ipad-pro-m1-feature.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1780\"><br>Gurman said \"the big iPhone 14 unveiling last month was probably it for Apple in 2022 in terms of major presentations,\" suggesting that any more new products this year would be announced with press releases, media briefings, and updates to Apple\'s online store.</p><p>Updated versions of the iPad Pro, MacBook Pro, and Mac mini â all with M2 series chips â are \"highly likely to launch\" before the end of 2022, according to Gurman. He also said an <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/06/28/apple-tv-rumored-features/\">updated Apple TV with an A14 chip</a> and extra RAM was \"getting closer and could potentially launch this year.\"<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>Apple Preparing iOS 16.0.3 With More Bug Fixes Following iPhone 14 Launch</strong></h2><p>iOS 16.0.2 was released last month with several bug fixes for iPhone 14 issues, excessive copy and paste permission prompts, and more. Now, evidence suggests that <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/03/apple-preparing-ios-16-0-3/\">Apple is planning to release iOS 16.0.3 with additional bug fixes</a> soon.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/mRG-FiNZ3pYHus31FUZkVVAcFdM=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16.0.3-Beta-Feature.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"iOS 16\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/mRG-FiNZ3pYHus31FUZkVVAcFdM=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16.0.3-Beta-Feature.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/jXxS56hc9CnGyeoSXQcRLNREKFo=/800x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16.0.3-Beta-Feature.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/_1qZQSCNg6KJ7lNWBBlLHUJWLBc=/1600x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16.0.3-Beta-Feature.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/jwzaWxVJMlZ7mqK7sscEYytqOMw=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16.0.3-Beta-Feature.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"2500\"><br>There are several remaining iOS 16 bugs that iOS 16.0.3 would hopefully address, including an issue with <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/09/20/iphone-14-pro-carplay-phone-calls-issue/\">low volume during CarPlay phone calls placed with iPhone 14 Pro models</a>, a string of text that can crash the Mail app, and more.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>Apple Rumored to Launch 27\" Mini-LED Display in Q1 2023</strong></h2><p>Apple is planning to <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/06/apple-mini-led-display-q1-2023/\">launch an external monitor with a 27-inch mini-LED display in the first quarter of 2023</a>, according to Display Supply Chain Consultants (DSCC) analyst Ross Young.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/GltJQdQ7POBF9zMFkMIssc_qZUQ=/400x0/article-new/2022/03/studio-display-3.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"studio display 3\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/GltJQdQ7POBF9zMFkMIssc_qZUQ=/400x0/article-new/2022/03/studio-display-3.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/DDbbjYSaBKOpOKrdU-7JWqNzGe0=/800x0/article-new/2022/03/studio-display-3.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/SnX9yUh2RUSs2R9Y6ZBtAuM9ZVM=/1600x0/article-new/2022/03/studio-display-3.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/OWLrf3ONlTcszbBzFukfZ9hxoCc=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/03/studio-display-3.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1920\"><br>Apple\'s upcoming display is said to feature mini-LED technology along with ProMotion support, allowing for up to a 120Hz refresh rate. It\'s unclear if the monitor would be branded as a Studio Display or have a different name.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>iPhone 14 Plus Reviews: Multi-Day Battery Life</strong></h2><p>The <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/review/iphone-14-plus/\">first reviews of the iPhone 14 Plus</a> hit just ahead of its <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/06/iphone-14-plus-australia-new-zealand/\">launch on Friday</a>, providing a closer look at the device in action.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/EgKHqo7HcbLwwwNiTRqloEVYa0w=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/iphone-14-iphone-14-plus-in-hand-feature.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"iphone 14 iphone 14 plus in hand feature\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/EgKHqo7HcbLwwwNiTRqloEVYa0w=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/iphone-14-iphone-14-plus-in-hand-feature.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/TkuO88EWyuQK2C0vPR5-eCcjy7Q=/800x0/article-new/2022/09/iphone-14-iphone-14-plus-in-hand-feature.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/9wQh4B6adCmiffEjTmrlYUgKE8s=/1600x0/article-new/2022/09/iphone-14-iphone-14-plus-in-hand-feature.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/SoYdH_NzNTxsRKaK6Fn4R-BjvP0=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/09/iphone-14-iphone-14-plus-in-hand-feature.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"2078\"><br>Reviews highlighted the iPhone 14 Plus\' impressively long battery life, while other new features include <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/09/30/apple-responds-to-crash-detection-test/\">car crash detection</a>, upcoming support for emergency texting via satellite starting in the U.S. and Canada, improved front and rear cameras, and more. U.S. pricing starts at $899.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>EU Passes Law to Switch iPhone to USB-C by End of 2024</strong></h2><p>The European Parliament this week voted overwhelmingly in favor of <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/04/eu-passes-law-to-switch-iphone-to-usb-c-in-2024/\">enforcing USB-C as a common charging port</a> across a wide range of devices, including the iPhone and AirPods, by the end of 2024.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/p6SRpXFyzxvLIaxRQetVqy8NTLE=/400x0/article-new/2021/09/USB-C-Over-Lightning-Feature.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"USB C Over Lightning Feature\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/p6SRpXFyzxvLIaxRQetVqy8NTLE=/400x0/article-new/2021/09/USB-C-Over-Lightning-Feature.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/ctpNFaqzF32tY0Z-1k8hIQsXyHQ=/800x0/article-new/2021/09/USB-C-Over-Lightning-Feature.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/O2sXT6D89LCNkWe1TyEov3hWjUA=/1600x0/article-new/2021/09/USB-C-Over-Lightning-Feature.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/jNcHn1JcWRHPb78DgWV61EwK1x8=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2021/09/USB-C-Over-Lightning-Feature.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"2500\"><br>Rumors suggest that <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/05/11/iphone-15-ditch-lightning-for-usb-c/\">all iPhone 15 models will be equipped with a USB-C port</a> next year, ahead of the EU\'s deadline. AirPods cases and MagSafe accessories are also expected to switch to USB-C.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>10 New iOS 16 Features Coming Later This Year</strong></h2><p>iOS 16 was released to the public over three weeks ago with a customizable Lock Screen, the ability to edit recently sent iMessages, and much more. And in the coming months, iPhone and iPad users have even more new features to look forward to.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/Y6RwJq_LNEiEYHo7E9ll0vq45oU=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16-Live-Activities-Sports-MLB.jpeg?lossy\" alt=\"iOS 16 Live Activities Sports MLB\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/Y6RwJq_LNEiEYHo7E9ll0vq45oU=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16-Live-Activities-Sports-MLB.jpeg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/rYms-Qih3w6pX-BXRXREAlA7SW0=/800x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16-Live-Activities-Sports-MLB.jpeg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/gb6rFHGiyg7gQsCb3yXJDtaPj1A=/1600x0/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16-Live-Activities-Sports-MLB.jpeg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/nZo6OLfSt02rTIHw8IqKlc6j6xs=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/09/iOS-16-Live-Activities-Sports-MLB.jpeg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1306\"><br>We\'ve rounded up <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/03/10-new-ios-16-features-coming-later-this-year/\">10 new features coming to the iPhone and iPad later this year</a>, according to Apple. Many of the features are part of iOS 16.1, which is currently in beta testing, but some of the features are not expected until later in the year.</p>', '2022-10-08 11:14:31', '2022-10-10 02:12:44'),
(5, 'Five Apple Products You Should Avoid Buying Right Now', 1, 1, '/files/posts/bcIEIm0m7b0Ih6p4OIHwaLZAXgovLI36WMv2TpZo.jpg', 2, '<p>Rumors suggest that Apple still has several new devices that are coming before the end of the year, including a range of Macs and iPads. It\'s not looking like we\'re going to <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/02/gurman-doubles-down-on-no-october-event/\">get an October event</a> in 2022, but refreshes are coming soon, probably via press release. If you\'re planning to buy a Mac or an <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipad/\">iPad</a>, make sure to check out our list to know what\'s safe to pick up now and what\'s not.</p><h2><a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipad-pro/\"><strong>iPad Pro</strong></a></h2><p>The <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipad-pro/\">iPad Pro</a> was last updated in April 2021, and we\'re expecting an updated version before the end of 2022. There are no design huge changes that we know of coming, but there are some features worth waiting for.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/uXEb_ccgqNfQMC5mWaJDjGMBE70=/400x0/article-new/2022/01/iPad-Pro-Big-Ol-Logo.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"iPad Pro Big Ol Logo\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/uXEb_ccgqNfQMC5mWaJDjGMBE70=/400x0/article-new/2022/01/iPad-Pro-Big-Ol-Logo.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/bpfaLzXHhuFHwkp69Cl-mZ2J4aY=/800x0/article-new/2022/01/iPad-Pro-Big-Ol-Logo.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/4KSbtd4gfoXhGOONYp_NoR41vik=/1600x0/article-new/2022/01/iPad-Pro-Big-Ol-Logo.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/VjKACp7vYXiNqB0NnCzYYv5EwU8=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/01/iPad-Pro-Big-Ol-Logo.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1398\"><br>Both the 11-inch and 12.9-inch âiPad Proâ models will get a refresh, but rumors suggest just the 12.9-inch model will have a mini-LED display, despite some information that had indicated Apple could bring the technology to both models.</p><p>Apple\'s updated âiPadâ Pros are expected to use the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m2/\">M2</a> chip that was first introduced in the new <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/macbook-air/\">MacBook Air</a> in June, bringing speed and performance improvements. There have also been rumors of wireless charging support, with Apple perhaps adding a new larger glass Apple logo at the back that would allow for <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/magsafe-battery-pack/\">MagSafe</a> charging.</p><p>Reverse wireless charging is also a possibility with the new âiPad Proâ models able to charge iPhones, AirPods, and other devices.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/2022-ipad/\"><strong>Low-Cost iPad</strong></a></h2><p>Apple has long offered a low-cost basic âiPadâ that is available at a ~$300 price point, but this year, the cheap âiPadâ is getting some trickle down features that have previously been limited to higher-end iPads.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/ZsPEnlsp9vBNPJodGDk70cqIDYg=/400x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-MySmartPrice-Render.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"10th Generation iPad MySmartPrice Render\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/ZsPEnlsp9vBNPJodGDk70cqIDYg=/400x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-MySmartPrice-Render.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/aDAzMu_lai2m1p5SLJf5ZnO7vZo=/800x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-MySmartPrice-Render.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/6S1GirgsUJWv1_IBhlQ83dJMopc=/1600x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-MySmartPrice-Render.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/Xo3yuxY3KqvT_am_cSGBv8_am48=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-MySmartPrice-Render.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1200\"><br>Apple is going to refresh the tired old design the low-cost âiPadâ has been using for years, introducing 10.5-inch display with a more modern look featuring flat edges and rounded corners. We\'ve previously seen this design used for the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipad-mini/\">iPad mini</a>, <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ipad-air/\">iPad Air</a>, and âiPad Proâ.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/OfMlMjTTg1nDLijaTtQg5RdVyGo=/400x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-Render-MySmartPrice-2.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"10th Generation iPad Render MySmartPrice 2\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/OfMlMjTTg1nDLijaTtQg5RdVyGo=/400x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-Render-MySmartPrice-2.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/VMzv7JQwBQKW2NVdk6CVk_XzCp4=/800x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-Render-MySmartPrice-2.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/axzqrb-mMbmMU-Gqiq7jxUQmPCk=/1600x0/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-Render-MySmartPrice-2.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/_H-tWn_XJLghv_EkHWS9dGkuzmc=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/08/10th-Generation-iPad-Render-MySmartPrice-2.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1200\"><br>The flat-edged design usually accompanies a bezel-free interface, but rumors right now suggest the âiPadâ will continue to have top and bottom bezels along with a <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/touch-id/\">Touch ID</a> Home button, but it remains to be seen if that\'s true. Apple could opt for the same power button âTouch IDâ design used for the âiPad miniâ and the âiPad Airâ.</p><p>With the exception of the low-cost âiPadâ, every âiPadâ uses a USB-C port, and Apple is going to swap Lightning for USB-C with the 10th-generation âiPadâ refresh.</p><p>We could also see some improvements to the camera, and a faster chip is a sure thing (likely the A14), but one thing the âiPadâ might lose is the headphone jack. Removing the headphone jack would bring the low-cost âiPadâ in line with the rest of the âiPadâ lineup.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/2023-macbook-pro/\"><strong>14 and 16-inch MacBook Pro</strong></a></h2><p>The <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m1-pro/\">M1 Pro</a> and <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m1-max/\">M1 Max</a> MacBook Pros came out in October of last year, and we might see new âM2â Pro and âM2â Max models released before the end of the year. New MacBook Pro models are said to be planned for release <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/08/28/macbook-pro-m2-pro-m2-max-development/\">as soon as this fall</a>, but there is a chance the timing could be pushed back because of supply constraints that Apple has been dealing with.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/OIbyjkkmj8Z1nM0f1pCGkh-Y1nE=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/macbook-pro-purple.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"macbook pro purple\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/OIbyjkkmj8Z1nM0f1pCGkh-Y1nE=/400x0/article-new/2022/09/macbook-pro-purple.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/HC36mgoLTV0UnCwQYNJcYdhevxM=/800x0/article-new/2022/09/macbook-pro-purple.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/_EPm6PqSKDlwtf6slCMB3EaTjzY=/1600x0/article-new/2022/09/macbook-pro-purple.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/Cpr8V5vj58sFo_i8yNpJ_vbnbAc=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/09/macbook-pro-purple.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"2500\"></p><h2><a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/2022-mac-mini/\"><strong>Mac Mini</strong></a></h2><p>There hasn\'t been a <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/mac-mini/\">Mac mini</a> refresh since 2020 when the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m1/\">M1</a> chip was added, but Apple doesn\'t yet plan on discontinuing the desktop machine. A refresh is in the works, and updated âMac miniâ devices could include âM2â and âM2â Pro chips.</p><p>We\'re not expecting any design changes, and the highest-end chips will likely be reserved for the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/mac-studio/\">Mac Studio</a>, which is like a hybrid of the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/mac-pro/\">Mac Pro</a> and the âMac miniâ.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>Apple TV</strong></h2><p>Apple last updated the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/apple-tv/\">Apple TV</a> in April of 2021, and it may be time for a refresh. Rumors suggest that there is a new model with an A14 chip and 4GB RAM <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/10/02/gurman-doubles-down-on-no-october-event/\">in development</a>, and it could be ready to launch before the end of 2022.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/mJdGQLPFxayrnei6gCXnBxqNZKY=/400x0/article-new/2021/04/apple-tv-4k-design-blue.jpg?lossy\" alt=\"apple tv 4k design blue\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/mJdGQLPFxayrnei6gCXnBxqNZKY=/400x0/article-new/2021/04/apple-tv-4k-design-blue.jpg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/MGDil64feT_ABLwjHLiE_S8vvPE=/800x0/article-new/2021/04/apple-tv-4k-design-blue.jpg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/3v19vFbmucJ4zepypqFAH3DbkIc=/1600x0/article-new/2021/04/apple-tv-4k-design-blue.jpg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/eSHXEcTK_i25qVCkEszUFSXwPG8=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2021/04/apple-tv-4k-design-blue.jpg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"2500\"><br>Apple analyst <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/ming-chi-kuo/\">Ming-Chi Kuo</a> has said several times this year that Apple is planning to <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/05/13/kuo-new-apple-tv-to-launch-second-half-2022/\">lower the price</a> of the âApple TVâ when it\'s refreshed, but whether that will actually happen remains to be seen.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/mac-pro/\"><strong>Bonus: Mac Pro</strong></a></h2><p>Since the âMac Proâ hasn\'t been updated since 2019 and doesn\'t yet use Apple silicon chips it\'s obvious that now is not a great time to buy. While we did hear some early 2022 rumors suggesting that the âMac Proâ could get a refresh before the end of the year, it\'s now looking like a new âMac Proâ isn\'t coming until 2023.</p><p><img src=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/3Akk_Ab12Li6ux9RzafA4TSa8lo=/400x0/article-new/2022/03/mac-pro-tower-close-up.jpeg?lossy\" alt=\"mac pro tower close up\" srcset=\"https://images.macrumors.com/t/3Akk_Ab12Li6ux9RzafA4TSa8lo=/400x0/article-new/2022/03/mac-pro-tower-close-up.jpeg?lossy 400w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/n8gj2XjozFmCVLA7rT_xn23q1y4=/800x0/article-new/2022/03/mac-pro-tower-close-up.jpeg?lossy 800w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/sKE5zQTFxEPS70BkPyGZ-z57E0Q=/1600x0/article-new/2022/03/mac-pro-tower-close-up.jpeg 1600w,https://images.macrumors.com/t/ZJMl_fIDwvrviTA4O9pcnWOEEeM=/2500x0/filters:no_upscale()/article-new/2022/03/mac-pro-tower-close-up.jpeg 2500w\" sizes=\"100vw\" width=\"1200\"><br>While we may have several months to go before the âMac Proâ sees an update, we don\'t recommend buying one right now. You\'re definitely going to want to wait on Apple to bring its ultra fast Apple silicon chips to its highest-end pro machine.</p><p>Rumors suggest that the âMac Proâ will use an âM2â Ultra, an upgrade to the <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/m1-ultra/\">M1 Ultra</a> first introduced in the âMac Studioâ, and an even more powerful âM2â Extreme chip. The âM1 Ultraâ features up to a 20-core CPU and a 64-core GPU, and the âM2â Ultra could be even more powerful.</p><p>The âM2â Extreme will be Apple\'s most powerful chip to date, and <i>Bloomberg</i>\'s <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/mark-gurman/\">Mark Gurman</a> <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2021/05/18/bloomberg-mac-pro-32-high-performance-cores/\">has said</a> that the chip could have upwards of 40 CPU cores and 128 GPU cores.<br>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>Wrap Up</strong></h2><p>Note that this list is based on rumors that we\'ve heard, so it\'s possible that some of these refreshes could be delayed into 2023. Timing Apple product releases is not always straightforward, but if you can wait on a purchase, it\'s a good idea to hold off until a new product announcement if you\'re concerned about having the latest and greatest device.</p><p>We have more product release timelines available for every Apple device in <a href=\"https://buyersguide.macrumors.com/\">our dedicated Buyer\'s Guide</a>, which is an invaluable resource for Apple fans.</p>', '2022-10-08 11:18:20', '2022-10-08 11:18:20'),
(6, 'Apple Seeds Eighth Public Beta of macOS 13 Ventura', 1, 1, '/files/posts/PoNwpqBgns6jwyUdDHiPwxx9BYOU25c7qr0lbVIe.jpg', 2, '<p>Apple today seeded the eighth beta of <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/macos-13/\">macOS Ventura</a> to its public beta testing group, allowing non-developers to test the new âmacOS Venturaâ operating system ahead of its release. The eighth beta comes following <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/2022/09/21/apple-releases-macos-ventura-public-beta-6/\">the seventh public beta</a> and it corresponds with tenth developer beta released earlier this week.</p><p>Public beta testers can download the macOS 13 Ventura update from the Software Update section of the System Preferences app after installing the proper profile from <a href=\"https://beta.apple.com/sp/betaprogram/\">Apple\'s beta software website</a>.</p><p>âmacOS Venturaâ introduces <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/stage-manager/\">Stage Manager</a>, a new multi-tasking option for focusing on a task while having other apps waiting in the wings. âStage Managerâ puts your main app front and center, tucking your other apps to the side for quick access.</p><p>Continuity Camera allows you to use your <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/iphone/\">iPhone</a> as a webcam for your Mac, offering much better camera quality than the built-in Mac camera. Apple is building special stands to hold the âiPhoneâ with a Mac, and there are neat features like Desk View, which uses the Ultra Wide lens.</p><p>Handoff now works with <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/guide/facetime/\">FaceTime</a> so you can answer calls on the Mac and then transfer them over to another device, and Messages is gaining undo, edit, and mark as unread features. SharePlay now works in Messages in addition to âFaceTimeâ, and the Mail app has been overhauled. Search is more relevant, emails can be scheduled, and there\'s even an option to undo an email for up to 10 seconds after it\'s sent.</p><p>Apple brought the Weather and Clock apps to the Mac, redesigned System Preferences and renamed it System Settings, and added support for Shared Tab Groups. Passwords are being replaced with more secure Passkeys in <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/ios-16/\">iOS 16</a> and âmacOS Venturaâ, and there are updates to Spotlight, Visual Lookup, Live Text, and more.</p><p>There are a ton of other features in âmacOS Venturaâ, and we have a full rundown available in our <a href=\"https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/macos-13/\">dedicated macOS Ventura roundup</a>.</p>', '2022-10-08 11:20:01', '2022-10-08 11:20:01'),
(7, 'Metaâs making it easier to report bugs in its Horizon VR app', 1, 1, '/files/posts/acpEjEgiePqHggjkBjEjh5DBaLVNmUeZp9QLnLrU.jpg', 3, '<blockquote><h2><i>Just mash all the face buttons on your controllers at once, which you may have been doing out of frustration anyways</i></h2></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meta <a href=\"https://click.linksynergy.com/deeplink?id=nOD/rLJHOac&amp;mid=43993&amp;u1=[]vg[p]23157326[t]w[r]https://www.theverge.com/tech[d]D&amp;murl=https://www.oculus.com/blog/meta-horizon-worlds-v78-release-notes/\">has updated Horizon Worlds</a>, its main virtual reality / âmetaverseâ app, to make it easier to report bugs. If you see something going wrong while using the app, you can now press and hold the A, B, X, and Y buttons on your controllers to bring up the âreport a problemâ window, where you can also attach a screenshot showing what went wrong.</p><p>If the experience seems familiar, it may be because itâs been in testing for a while; according to Meta spokesperson Kelsi Horn, there were early tests available to âa subset of creatorsâ as far back as April 2021. Since then, according to Horn, Meta has improved the UI and is now rolling it out to everyone. Horn added that âbugs reported through this tool are individually triaged by members of the Horizon Worlds team,â so it seems like Metaâs definitely trying to pay attention to the reports.</p><p>Thatâs not necessarily a surprise. In <a href=\"https://click.linksynergy.com/deeplink?id=nOD/rLJHOac&amp;mid=43993&amp;u1=[]vg[p]23157326[t]w[r]https://www.theverge.com/tech[d]D&amp;murl=https://www.oculus.com/blog/meta-horizon-worlds-v78-release-notes/\">the blog post announcing the update</a>, Meta admits that a competition it ran in the app couldnât be fairly judged because âthe platform was unstable and had too many bugs near the end of the competition.â A <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2022/10/6/23391895/meta-facebook-horizon-worlds-vr-social-network-too-buggy-leaked-memo\">recent report</a> from my colleague Alex Heath reveals that Horizonâs bugginess has been a sore spot within the company; the team behind it is in a âquality lockdownâ for the rest of 2022 to iron out the bugs before more people start using the app (early this year, <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2022/2/17/22939297/meta-social-vr-platform-horizon-300000-users\">Alex reported</a> that it had around 300,000 monthly users). In a memo, Metaâs VP of metaverse, Vishal Shah, told employees: âfeedback from our creators, users, playtesters, and many of us on the team is that the aggregate weight of papercuts, stability issues, and bugs is making it too hard for our community to experience the magic of Horizon.â</p><p>&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p>why the team who built the app doesnât spend more time in it themselves.</p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg, whose vision has largely driven the companyâs metaverse efforts, has <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2022/8/19/23313469/mark-zuckerberg-horizon-worlds-screenshot-memes-response-upgrades\">promised to share details</a> about âmajor updates to Horizon and avatar graphicsâ at the companyâs Connect conference on October 11th. The companyâs also set to announce its next-gen headset, the Quest Pro, which seemingly <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2022/9/11/23347979/meta-quest-pro-leak-vr-project-cambria-headset\">leaked in spectacular fashion</a> last month. Of course, new graphics and new hardware could mean a host of new bugs as well, so this upgrade to the reporting system is well-timed.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>', '2022-10-08 11:25:20', '2022-10-08 11:25:20'),
(9, 'Is Tailwind CSS Worth It?', 1, 1, '/files/posts/iqWEfVKTA6yr4EjAEhvmQyWG6HDhhra9doJWD0R2.jpg', 3, '<p>The Good, the Bad, and the Ugly of Utility-Based CSS</p><p>CSS utility classes have been around for a long time now. However, their popularity has recently skyrocketed with the adoption of libraries like <a href=\"https://tailwindcss.com/\">Tailwind CSS</a>. In this article, I want to share my thoughts, opinions, and hot takes about how tools like this change the user experience for developers and alter our relationship with the DOM. Feel free to completely disagree with me!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h2><strong>What Problem Are We Trying To Solve?</strong></h2><p>In my view, the goal of a utility class-based system is to decouple. You can decouple your component styles from the HTML structure. You can decouple your rules from grouped component styles. At first glance, this sounds great, and it is. However, this methodology comes with its own set of problems.</p><p>CSS utility classes, or Functional CSS, are all about thinking small. The goal is to break up your app into a ton of little tiny classes that do one thing. You may have heard of a similar concept in programming called the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-responsibility_principle\">Single Responsibility Principle</a> or Functional Programming. In CSS, the same concept exists. For example, they might center text in a div with a class called .text-center. These tiny classes are then composed together on a DOM element until the desired result is achieved.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>It sounds straightforward at first but, while focusing on the micro we lose sight of the macro. In <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PcrzsCdoFoY\">this interview</a>, Sarah Dayan gives an amazing walk down memory lane about the recent history of CSS. She elegantly describes not only the technologies that were used but, expands on the philosophy behind them. Even though this video is a few years old now, I think itâs still relevant. She leads us to a logical path of using Atomic CSS and Design Systems to build modern websites and apps. Sheâs not wrong.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>She is also currently found on the homepage of the Tailwind CSS website. There she is quoted as saying that Tailwind is the only framework that has scaled on large teams. I think she makes some great points but misses a crucial one. Tailwind is UGLY! Iâm not the first person to say this. The internet has plenty of places you can find critiques of Tailwind.</p><p>Iâd like to focus on the actual UX for developers who use it. When asked about the ugly HTML that is generated by a pure utility class approach, even she was backed into a corner around the 14 min mark and was forced to admit that âyou can get used to almost anythingâ. My question is, should we?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p><i>Abstraction reduces cognitive load</i></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote><h2>&nbsp;</h2><h2><strong>The UX of Utility Classes</strong></h2><p>I worry that sometimes as developers we get so obsessed with DRY principles and smaller bundles, that we forget our own needs as the people building this stuff. Ease of use, productivity, and general happiness while using the methodology <i>matter</i>. I donât care what the bundle size looks like if it makes my life much harder. We focus on the objective more than the subjective. Which makes sense, until it doesnât. Thereâs a reason why we donât create web apps in raw JavaScript. Itâs tedious, hard to read, and hard to organize. This is how I feel about a pure CSS utility class approach.</p><p>Imagine having to order your dinner by listing all of the ingredients instead of just saying the name of the dish. For example, you <i>could</i> sit down in a restaurant, wait for the waiter to come over, then say I want a âtraditional Italian meal consisting of long thin wheat noodles, tomatoes that have been turned into a liquid, and small chunks of beef that have been shaped into spheresâ. This is how utility classes work. Iâd rather just order âspaghetti and meatballsâ and call it a day. ð¤·ââï¸ð</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In addition to producing some headache-inducing HTML templates, this style of CSS encourages less semantic HTML. Donât take my word for it though, go look at the Tailwind CSS website. I see lots of â<a href=\"https://www.hackterms.com/div%20soup\">div soup</a>â in the examples.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Hereâs a sample of what Iâm talking about from their website. Do you have any idea what this is without rendering it? I sure donât.</p><blockquote><p>&lt;div class=\"space-y-2\"&gt;<br>&nbsp; &lt;div class=\"relative\"&gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;div class=\"bg-slate-100 dark:bg-slate-700 rounded-full overflow-hidden\"&gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;div<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; class=\"bg-cyan-500 dark:bg-cyan-400 w-1/2 h-2\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; role=\"progressbar\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; aria-label=\"music progress\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; aria-valuenow=\"1456\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; aria-valuemin=\"0\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; aria-valuemax=\"4550\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &gt;&lt;/div&gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;/div&gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;div<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; class=\"ring-cyan-500 dark:ring-cyan-400 ring-2 absolute left-1/2 top-1/2 w-4 h-4 -mt-2 -ml-2 flex items-center justify-center bg-white rounded-full shadow\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;div<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; class=\"w-1.5 h-1.5 bg-cyan-500 dark:bg-cyan-400 rounded-full ring-1 ring-inset ring-slate-900/5\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &gt;&lt;/div&gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;/div&gt;<br>&nbsp; &lt;/div&gt;<br>&nbsp; &lt;div class=\"flex justify-between text-sm leading-6 font-medium tabular-nums\"&gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;div class=\"text-cyan-500 dark:text-slate-100\"&gt;24:16&lt;/div&gt;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;div class=\"text-slate-500 dark:text-slate-400\"&gt;75:50&lt;/div&gt;<br>&nbsp; &lt;/div&gt;<br>&lt;/div&gt;</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Can you imagine quickly scanning this HTML file to find the correct div to update with this<i> lack of context</i>? By context I mean, when you look at the template, you know what it is. Tailwind goes against the old Object-Oriented CSS patterns and exchanges them for total anarchy. Heaven forbid were you to find a CSS bug. You might have to adjust classes on <i>several</i> elements before finding the exact px-3 class you need. As humans, we need abstract concepts to use as mental models to save time and do value mapping in our brains. The infamous .card class which has been used in several different CSS frameworks and apps, was hugely popular because it scratched our primal itch to attach meaning to a thing. Pure utility class templates throw all that out the window.</p><h2>&nbsp;</h2><h2><strong>The Best of Both Worlds</strong></h2><p>OK, letâs get to the <i>less</i> negative part of this article. After all, I do like the idea of making things atomic! I just donât think that classes are the place to do it. We really can make better design systems without reinventing the wheel with every new component. If you want to get Atomic, you need to go even smaller than classes. You need to use <a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/--*\">CSS Custom Properties</a>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I recently discovered a library that perfectly sums up my thoughts on this. Itâs called <a href=\"https://open-props.style/\">Open Props</a> and I highly recommend you check it out. It solves both problems elegantly. How do I create meaning and abstractions in my HTML while also creating global styles that are reusable?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>You can see in the Open Props examples that they mostly use meaningful class names. Which leads to better âscannabilityâ in our HTML and faster troubleshooting. Take this example:</p><p>.hero {<br>&nbsp; line-height: var(--font-lineheight-1);<br>&nbsp; font-size: var(--font-size-fluid-3);<br>&nbsp; font-weight: var(--font-weight-9);<br>&nbsp; font-family: var(--font-sans);<br>}</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Everyone knows what a âheroâ element is. With a pure utility class approach, this would become 4 separate classes to maintain the individual element. Now, theyâre grouped in one spot which makes it easier to read and understand. Oh and by the way, it wonât add extra noise to your framework-specific DOM attributes such as Angularâs *ngFor .</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>This also allows you to continue using other class naming conventions such as <a href=\"http://getbem.com/introduction/\">BEM</a> or <a href=\"https://cube.fyi/#what-does-cube-css-stand-for\">CUBE</a>. The choice is yours. To be fair, you could even combine this with utility classes if you prefer. However, I still argue that youâre making a big trade-off by doing so.</p><p>.fs-lg {<br>&nbsp; font-size: var(--font-size-8);<br>}&lt;div class=\"fs-lg\"&gt;Hello World&lt;/div&gt; &nbsp;&lt;-- you lose the meaning again</p><h2>&nbsp;</h2><h2><strong>Conclusion</strong></h2><p>To wrap things up, I just want to reiterate that I support building more global styling rules that help us build web apps in an âatomicâ way. I just donât believe classes are the place to do it. Tailwind is probably not going anywhere and we need to accept it but, I donât want to lose sight of what weâre losing in the process.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>I am excited about libraries like Open Props which might be the best way to find a middle ground between reusability and meaning. I hope this article gave you some food for thought when choosing you\'re next CSS framework. Let me know what you think in the comments!</p>', '2022-10-08 11:32:39', '2022-10-08 11:32:39'),
(10, 'AWS EKS cluster networking', 1, 1, '/files/posts/odPmosXDbT1dguhmJyT6m6dYuU1pSfygZkQkKFVY.png', 1, '<p>On AWS Kubernetes requires an understanding the EKS networking to the cluster control plane with worker node reach. This blog is just explain networking on EKS and resolution to investigating and troubleshooting. when you have a problem with cluster communication between EKS control-plan(EKS VPC) to worker nodes(Subnet).</p><p>EKS Cluster</p><ul><li>VPC</li><li>ClusterIP CIDR</li><li>Subnet</li><li>ENI</li><li>Security Group</li><li>NetworkACLs</li><li>RouteTable</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>EKS with public and Private subnet</p><p>EKS with public and Private subnet</p><p>Consider, EKS control plan needs to use ENI that reseverd for Amazon EKS to comunicate the nodes, and on each of instances are attached eni which control inbound/outbound by network ACLs on VPC Subnet and router by routetable for contrrol traffice to CIDR range. The instances policy are applied on-top by security group layer.</p><p>Cluster Add-on Plugins</p><ul><li>CoreDNS</li><li>Kube-Proxy</li><li>VPC-CNI</li></ul><p><strong>Cluster IPs and PODs IPs</strong></p><p><picture><source srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/max/640/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/max/720/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/max/750/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/max/786/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/max/828/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1100/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png 1400w\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"><img src=\"https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/1*TjP9HYojvdNrdq4BJ3D5kA.png\" alt=\"\"></picture></p><p>The Cluster IPs is IP for internal cluster comunication it depend by cluster CIDR range at first time cluster has been created.</p><p><picture><source srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/max/640/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/max/720/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/max/750/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/max/786/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/max/828/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1100/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png 1400w\" sizes=\"(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"><img src=\"https://miro.medium.com/max/1400/1*qosV6Oe-H9TOC8SzERGTMg.png\" alt=\"\"></picture></p><p>The IPs of pods these are reserved from instance with secondary private IPv4 it depend by subnet.</p><p><picture><source srcset=\"https://miro.medium.com/max/640/1*Ab27gVHKdJhj8oxtWlUAlA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/max/720/1*Ab27gVHKdJhj8oxtWlUAlA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/max/750/1*Ab27gVHKdJhj8oxtWlUAlA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/max/786/1*Ab27gVHKdJhj8oxtWlUAlA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/max/828/1*Ab27gVHKdJhj8oxtWlUAlA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/max/1100/1*Ab27gVHKdJhj8oxtWlUAl